<DOCNO> AP890719-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
britains top law officer pledged wednesday to 
press ahead with reforms of the legal system despite fierce 
opposition from most judges barristers and even the attorney 
general 
lord mackay lord high chancellor presented his final propoals 
in a policy document called a white paper which parliament will 
debate 
prime minister margaret thatcher appointed mackay to the cabinet 
post in 1987 and told him to propose reforms to do away with 
restrictive legal practices britains legal system has been 
criticized for years as expensive and inaccessible to those who 
cannot afford high fees 
mackays proposals probably will become law since mrs thatchers 
government has a 100seat majority in the 650seat house of commons 
mackay made some concessions in the white paper but kept most of 
his original proposals including ending the monopoly that 
barristers have on arguing cases in court he would open that 
practice to solicitors who now are confined to consulting with 
clients 
solicitors and barristers charge for their cases even if they 
lose mackay has proposed that lawyers in civil cases be paid only 
if they win a case 
as a concession he said a proposed committee on conduct would 
not be empowered to decide the rules governing the legal profession 
but would have an advisory role instead mackay proposed that he 
and senior judges decide any changes in the rules 
the governments aim in all these changes is to make the legal 
system of this country more straightforward more flexible and 
above all more responsive to the citizens choices and needs whilst 
at the same time maintaining the standards necessary to achieve 
justice he wrote in the white paper 
in the past six months of debate over the proposals judges 
threatened to halt court work although they eventually backed down 
and barristers launched a national campaign of denunciation 
attorney general sir patrick mayhew said he would consider 
resigning although he didnt 
david tench legal chief of the consumers association said lord 
mackays proposals would be a fundamental step in the right 
direction toward a better more responsive legal profession 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

