<TEXT>
archaeologists using shovels and other 
garden tools found a human skull bone tuesday underneath a marker 
honoring the five men believed to be victims of 19thcentury 
cannibal alferd packer 
its definitely human said archaeologist jim ayres as the 
bone was unearthed in the apparent grave at noon 
walter birkby a physical anthropologist at arizona state museum 
in tucson said it was a left temporal bone found in the human 
skull it will be shipped to the university of arizona for analysis 
the archaeologists are participating in a dig organized by george 
washington university law professor james starrs who wants to learn 
the truth about the 1874 cannibalism case he hopes to determine how 
the five men were murdered and whether packer consumed their remains 
packer formed a party of utah men to search for gold in the san 
juan mountains but the group became snowbound on the 9000foot 
mountain ridge in 1874 
packer claimed that one of the men shannon bell killed the 
other four while packer was away from camp packer said he then 
killed bell in selfdefense and consumed the remains of the five men 
to survive 
despite his claim packer was convicted of murdering one of the 
prospectors in 1883 after that verdict was overturned by the state 
supreme court packer was retried and convicted of manslaughter he 
was sentenced to serve 40 years in prison but was paroled in 1901 
and died six years later 
the reputed gravesite of the five victims has been set off by a 
marker which honors the five men who were murdered on this spot 
early in the year 1874 while pioneering for mineral resources of the 
san juan country but researchers are uncertain whether the sign 
marks the actual spot where packer victims are buried 
working in shortsleeved shirts hiking shorts and hats ayres 
birkby and some of their graduate students dug about 6 inches under 
the marker tuesday before locating parallel rows of rock that they 
speculated marked the graves of the five men the human bone was 
found a short time later 
ayres said the group had a photograph of the rocks in formation 
that was taken in 1909 but he and birkby were cautious about what 
may lie below the rocks 
well clean it up shoot it plot it on the map and then dig 
some more birkby said we dont know how deep it is 
to this day the packer case has triggered broad human interest 
from embellished legend to jokes and the wry amusement is shared by 
scientists on the dig as well as the onlookers 
starrs has nicknamed the dig area the bone zone and is 
selling tshirts bearing a skeleton and the words gimme five the 
alferd packer expedition july 1989 to help offset the costs of the 
trip 
other tshirts for sale in the area proclaim have a friend for 
dinner and alferd packer serving his fellow man 
