<TEXT>
the suicide rate among elderly americans has 
increased in recent years federal statistics show 
the suicides rate among people aged 75 to 84 jumped 21 percent 
from 208 per 100000 people in 1979 to 252 per 100000 in 1986 
according to data compiled by the national center for health 
statistics 
during that same period the suicide rate for all americans edged 
up 5 percent from 121 per 100000 to 128 per 100000 
the figures included in a detailed national mortality report for 
1986 did not include an explanation for the increase 
the 21 percent suicide jump among the 7584 group was followed by 
a 16 percent increase for people aged 85 and over their rate rose 
from 179 per 100000 to 208 between 1979 and 1986 
for the 6574 age group the suicide increase was nearly 11 
percent from 178 to 197 per 100000 there was a 2 percent rise 
from 166 to 170 among people aged 55 to 64 
the figures showed a sharp 50 percent increase in the rate for 
youngsters aged 5 to 14 but that rate was still so low that only a 
small change results in a big percentage difference the rate rose 
from 04 per 100000 in 1979 to 08 in 1986 
for the 1524 age group suicides were up 5 percent from 124 per 
100000 to 131 in 1986 
other rates were 157 per 100000 in 1986 for people aged 25 to 
34 down from 163 in 1979 152 per 100000 population for those 35 
to 44 down from 154 and 164 per 100000 for people 45 to 54 
down from 165 
