<TEXT>
the authors of a book released today said they 
have compiled the most comprehensive guide to the soviet nuclear 
arsenal and that the red armys stockpile is dwindling because of 
mikhail gorbachevs policies 
we believe that the arsenal is declining that it peaked some 
time last year one of the authors thomas b cochran told a news 
conference theyre not ahead of us and were not ahead of them 
the fact is both can do a lot of damage to the other 
the book a slick oversized redcovered paperback entitled 
soviet nuclear weapons claims the soviet arsenal grew because 
of the perception of how to achieve national security the 
advancement of certain foreign policy goals the desire for 
recognition as a superpower domestic political struggles 
bureaucratic inertia and military service rivalry 
with soviet president gorbachevs doctrine of necessary 
defensive sufficiency however the arsenal is declining the 
authors say 
they are and will continue in the future to get rid of their 
relics just as we did robert s norris one of the authors said 
in an interview tuesday they are 40 percent larger than we are 
and at first glance thats alarming but look at why and theres 
less concern 
soviet nuclear forces are following the us pattern of the 
past 10 to 20 years certain military missions that once used 
nuclear weapons began to be phased out a statement about the book 
said the weapon was either not replaced or replaced with a 
conventional system 
but william m arkin one of the other authors warns one 
should not confuse technical obsolescence with real decisions to 
remove weapons 
arkin points out that a large percentage of the arsenals of both 
the united states and the soviet union are not included in any of 
the arms control negotiations 
and those are the nuclear weapons that are most likely to cause 
nuclear war he said adding that 14000 of the 33000 soviet 
warheads are not included in any of the arms talks he cites bombs 
on jet fighters artillery and naval weapons 
norris said the book relied heavily on us government 
statistics many of them obtained through the freedom of information 
act 
this book seeks to put together everything we know about the 
topic in one place he said pointing out the authors used 
extensive footnotes to document their research 
what is lacking norris readily acknowledged is the specifics 
from the soviet union 
we didnt get any information from the soviets he said 
the next step is to have the soviets tell us more about out its 
beginning to happen we hope this book will be a lever 
