cabinet secretary louis sullivan on wednesday 
backed away from supporting local needleexchange programs to help 
stem the spread of aids and told congress the bush administration 
opposes such programs 
the health and human services secretary said that after talking 
with aids and drug abuse experts and members of congress he 
believes at this time there is insufficient scientific evidence to 
conclude that needleexchange programs are effective in curbing the 
spread of the aids virus 
he also said the administration is opposed because of concern 
that programs that provide clean needles to drug addicts could be 
viewed as sanctioning iv drug abuse 
we await better solutions to the twin scourges of aids and iv 
drug abuse he told the subcommittee 
sullivans comments during a more than twohour appearance before 
the house energy and commerce health subcommittee were a departure 
from statements he made in an interview with the association press 
in march 
in the interview the secretary said he did not subscribe to 
the view that it needle exchange condones drug abuse he also 
said that while he did not favor a federal needleexchange program 
because of strong opposition in some communities the federal 
government could provide trained health officials and other support 
for communities that want such programs 
he said in march it is an idea that certainly deserves some 
investigation to see if it does work and if it does then that would 
then strengthen those other communities where there is concern that 
it is sending the wrong message 
he told members of the subcommittee we want to gather all the 
information that we can about these programs and because of the 
fact that there has not been evidence clear evidence that these 
programs are effective we are not prepared to advocate or come 
forth with programs 
sullivans ealier statements alarmed some in the bush 
administration including drug czar william bennett who opposes 
needle exchange programs presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater 
said bush is opposed to exchangeable needles under any condition 
sullivan said his department planned no efforts to conduct its 
own evaluation of the effectiveness of needleexchange programs but 
he said the national institute on drug abuse which is part of hhs 
would consider applications for research grants for such an 
evaluation 
however he said it will be difficult to develop an effective 
methodology 
pressed by rep henry waxman dcalif subcommittee chairman 
sullivan agreed to convene a panel of scientists to determine how 
the effectiveness of these programs can be evaluated scientifically 
waxman asked sullivan to report back to the subcommittee with the 
panels recommendations 
needleexchange programs are under way in england australia 
sweden and the netherlands as well as several us cities 
including new york city tacoma wash and boulder colo 
sullivan said the studies evaluating the effectiveness of some of 
these programs is not convincing because none has compared a 
group of addicts receiving clean needles with a group that is not 
also it is not clear whether findings that show decreased needle 
sharing and no increase in drug abuse are resulting from other 
factors he said 
