<TEXT>
measles vaccinations are being recommended for as 
many as 100 million people 32 or younger and two doses of vaccine 
are being urged for children after reports of measles outbreaks in 
18 states 
the recommendations from the american academy of pediatrics and 
the centers for disease control were prompted by an estimated 350 
percent increase in measles cases nationwide this year dr william 
atkinson an epidemiologist at the cdc in atlanta said wednesday 
cdc figures show that 7563 measles cases have been reported 
nationwide this year through july 9 compared to 1586 cases during 
the same period last year 
its the worst outbreak in nine years atkinson said 
measles hits most often in winter and most outbreaks wind down 
with the onslaught of midsummer heat he said 
its primarily innercity black and hispanic children who dont 
get into the healthcare system very easily who are affected 
atkinson said 
the disease characterized by a high fever cough and rash is 
extremely contagious and generally more severe in adults 
most children are routinely vaccinated when they are about 15 
months old but vaccines produced before 1980 are less resistant to 
heat and often less potent said dr martha lepow a member of the 
academys committee on infectious diseases 
the academy and the cdc both say immunization efforts should be 
aimed at schoolage children the group most affected by the current 
outbreaks 
the academy recommends children be given combined vaccinations 
for measles mumps and rubella or german measles at 15 months of 
age and again when they enter middle school or junior high 
the organization based in suburban elk grove village also 
recommends revaccination for anyone entering college adults in 
healthcare professions and adults 32 or younger who live in a 
region where theres an outbreak said ms lepow 
most people over 32 contracted measles during epidemics that hit 
the country before 1957 and are naturally immune atkinson said 
atkinson said the cdc supports the academys recommendations and 
will issue similar guidelines within the next few months 
the cdc believes that anyone 32 or younger who hasnt had measles 
roughly 100 million people should be revaccinated he said 
the academys policy also does not apply to anyone who has had 
measles said ms lepow a professor of pediatrics at albany medical 
college in albany ny 
in highrisk areas children should be vaccinated at 12 months of 
age the academy says those vaccinated before their first birthday 
should have a second vaccination at 15 months and a third upon 
entry to middle and junior high school 
children under 1 often dont respond to the vaccine ms lepow 
said 
the academy formerly recommended a single dose at age 15 months 
and did not have a revaccination policy for those school age and 
older except in the cases of outbreaks 
no unusual reactions have been associated with revaccination the 
academy said in a news release but noted that women should not be 
pregnant when receiving the vaccine or for three months afterwards 
about 60 outbreaks in 45 states have been reported this year 
atkinson said 
outbreaks are considered active in 18 states he said the cdc 
defines an outbreak as five or more cases believed to be linked in a 
specified area 
texas has been the hardest hit with 1800 cases reported so far 
in houston alone he said 
other states where outbreaks are considered active are alabama 
arizona california connecticut florida illinois kentucky 
michigan minnesota nebraska new jersey ohio oregon 
pennsylvania tennessee utah and wisconsin 
</TEXT>
