<TEXT>
the treasury department pleaded with congress 
on wednesday to raise the national debt ceiling and announced its 
first step to avoid exceeding the limit if congress fails to act 
before its august recess 
our immediate need is for legislation to increase the debt 
limit treasury undersecretary robert r glauber told a senate 
finance subcommittee without the extension he said the government 
would have problems issuing payroll and social security checks 
glauber echoed treasury secretary nicholas f brady who wrote 
senate leaders last month urging an increase of the debt ceiling by 
300 billion from the current limit of 28 trillion the house has 
passed similar legislation 
meanwhile in its first action to insure that the debt limit is 
not exceeded the department announced it is suspending until 
further notice the sale of special securities for state and local 
governments 
the government has been forced to suspend such sales at other 
times when congress was unable to agree on legislation raising the 
national debt limit 
state and local governments buy the special treasury securities 
as a temporary investment vehicle for money they raise in the bond 
market 
if the securities are not available for purchase state and local 
governments could be forced to cancel planned bond sales leading to 
turmoil in the municipal bond market 
glauber warned the finance subcommittee of other effects of 
congressional inaction on the debt limit increase 
without an increase in the debt limit by aug 1 full 
investment of the social security trust funds may not be possible 
he said 
the law requires the treasury secretary to invest trust fund 
assests in interestbearing government securities the securities 
are a form of government debt and are counted with other government 
bonds and notes against the debt limit 
while congress normally appropriates the money to cover any 
interest lost to the trust funds during a period when they cannot be 
invested this action has been criticized by groups representing the 
elderly 
glauber also said that if congress did not take action before 
its monthlong recess beginning aug 5 the treasury would not be 
able to make the government payroll for september 
this would include writing payroll and pension checks exceeding 
23 billion 
glauber also proposed changing the method of measuring debt on 
government securities from the current face amount to one based 
on the actual value of the security at a particular time 
for instance some treasury securities worth 10000 are sold at 
a discount accruing interest over time until they are worth their 
face value at maturity 
