<TEXT>
sen richard bryan dnev urged energy 
secretary james d watkins on wednesday to scrap plans to build a 
highlevel nuclear waste dump in nevada saying delays now made it 
certain the site would not be ready in time 
the energy department has set a 2003 target date for opening the 
underground repository but a series of technical and political 
obstacles have put that target in doubt 
the dump would hold waste from commercial nuclear plants that 
will be dangerously radioactive for at least 10000 years it is 
about 100 miles northwest of las vegas 
nuclear utilities are desperate for a permanent storage facility 
because the cost of keeping waste in temporary storage at 
reactor plants is escalating 
bryan said watkins has legal authority to halt the departments 
work at nevadas yucca mountain which so far has been limited to 
preparing a means of characterizing the site or determining its 
geologic suitability as a dump 
bryan said in a letter to watkins that the department should turn 
away from the underground storage idea to consider ways of storing 
the waste at reactor sites in dry casks or other methods 
i believe you can restore scientific integrity and rational 
public policy to a program that if continued is destined to fail 
for scientific economic and political reasons bryan said in his 
letter 
a nuclear regulatory commission geologist in a report made 
public tuesday said preliminary energy department analyses of 
volcanic potentials near yucca mountain had grossly understated the 
chances of an eruption 
the geologist john trapp said the odds of an eruption during 
the next 10000 years may be about one in six rather than the 
onein30 chance cited by other scientists 
sen harry reid dnev said on the senate floor wednesday that 
trapp was a hero 
he did what no one expected him to do tell it like it really 
is and let the chips fall where they may reid said adding that 
the proposal for storing nuclear waste at yucca mountain was 
seriously flawed and an economic disaster 
a nuclear waste repository under yucca mountain would be as 
smart as storing nitroglycerin in a boiling tea pot he said 
watkins has said he feels bound by the nuclear waste policy act 
amendments of 1987 to carry out a suitability study at yucca 
mountain even though the state government has gone on record 
opposing the project 
christina sankey a department spokeswoman said in response to 
bryans letter that while she was not sure watkins had seen it the 
plea would not change his mind that it is too early to give up on 
yucca mountain 
he opposes such a move she said 
</TEXT>
