<TEXT>
the head of the commodity futures trading 
commission says it is too soon to impose restrictions on dual 
trading the system in which brokers can trade for themselves and 
their customers at the same time 
at a hearing tuesday on legislation that would reauthorize the 
15yearold agency cftc chairwoman wendy gramm said it was 
conducting a study on dual trading that is to be completed in 
october 
since our analysis is not yet complete we believe that a 
statutory restriction based on specific volume levels would be 
premature she told exasperated members of the house subcommittee 
on conservation credit and rural development 
in dual trading floor brokers at a futures exchange may trade 
for their own accounts and that of their customers a practice that 
critics claim creates a conflict of interest 
the reauthorizing legislation sponsored by subcommittee chairman 
glenn english dokla and rep e thomas coleman of missouri the 
ranking republican would place sharp restrictions on dual trading 
in the futures markets 
englishs subcommittee began an investigation of dual trading in 
response to revelations in january of an undercover fbi probe of 
alleged abuses by as many as 100 traders at the chicago board of 
trade and the chicago mercantile exchange the nations two largest 
futures markets 
the proposed legislation would bar dual trading except for 
futures that have an average daily trading volume of fewer than 
7000 contracts 
the legislation also would require exchanges to adopt procedures 
allowing them to reconstruct the times of trades to the nearest 
30second interval an accurate reconstruction of the brokers terms 
and time of a trade known as an audit trail allows investigators 
to determine whether brokers are abusing dual trading rules 
because no system can detect every type of trade violation said 
ms gramm we believe that a careful analysis is necessary before 
increasing the trade timing standard to 30 seconds or less 
english however noted that the cftc conducted 14 studies on 
audit trails in the fourth quarter of its fiscal year 
theyve just about studied everything to death said the 
chairman its time that you act 
on other topics ms gramm told subcommittee members that her 
agency had little more than a consulting role in last weeks 
emergency action on soybean futures in chicago 
ms gramm said her agency was now reviewing the emergency order 
by the chicago board of trade for soybean traders to liquidate large 
holdings 
while cbot officials consulted her agency before issuing the 
order ms gramm indicated little other action was taken by the 
cftc which regulates futures and commodity options markets 
rep david r nagle diowa asked ms gramm what she did after 
cbot officials notified her that they were ordering all traders to 
reduce their july contract soybean holdings to 1 million bushels by 
the close of trading thursday 
i thanked them for the information said ms gramm adding 
that she neither approved nor discouraged the action under repeated 
questioning by subcommittee members however ms gramm conceded 
that no opposition was a form of approval 
i dont find your answers very confidenceinspiring said 
nagle 
ms gramm maintained that under law the cbot and other exchanges 
are selfregulatory and bear the first responsibility to maintain 
orderly trading in and liquidation of futures contracts 
several subcommittee members criticized the cftc for a 
businessasusual type of approach after ms gramm said no major 
legislative changes were being sought despite ongoing probes at 
commodities exchanges in chicago and new york as well as the soybean 
affair at the cbot 
english said during a break in the hearing that he was dismayed 
by the attitude of the agencys officials 
the cftc has a great deal of authority but they dont seem 
willing to use it he added 
