<TEXT>
the alar controversy has spread to the 
cherry crop with south korea and taiwan virtually halting imports 
of washington cherries even though cherry industry officials say the 
chemical was not used on the 1989 crop 
several large containers of washington cherries are reportedly 
stalled in a south korean port while the south korean government 
decides whether to admit them officials said tuesday 
there has been no government action against cherry imports in 
taiwan but consumer fears have destroyed the market there 
officials said 
south korea and taiwan are small markets for washington which 
produces about onethird of the nations cherries but they had been 
doubling their cherry purchases for the past few years 
it means loss of a growing market overseas for washington 
cherries said brent heinemann a trade specialist for the 
washington state department of agriculture 
heinemann said at least two 1700box containers of washington 
cherries are sitting at the port of inchon south korea and hadnt 
cleared customs as of last week 
they may not be sold said heinemann who was on a trade 
mission to south korea last week and saw washington cherries 
disappear from markets the day after the controversy began 
ted zacher president of the chief wenatchee fruit packing 
cooperative in wenatchee said all air freight shipments of cherries 
to south korea have stopped 
we dont use alar on cherries zacher said where they got 
that information i dont know 
the washington cherry industry has scrambled to produce test 
results showing that alar is no longer used on their crop but the 
test results have not been believed or reported in south korea 
heinemann said 
the taiwanese council of agriculture should move to reassure 
consumers that us cherries are safe said bill bryant of the 
northwest horticultural council in yakima 
in a letter to the us department of agriculture last week 
bryant said that a test commissioned by the fruit industry trade 
group found no traces of alar in 10 washington cherry samples 
alar residues should not be an issue with cherries the 
letter said 
washington growers had hoped to ship 100000 20pound boxes of 
cherries to taiwan and south korea this year worth about 2 million 
wholesale bryant said 
this year well be fortunate to ship 30000 boxes bryant 
said 
even that would be a huge jump from the 7400 boxes shipped to 
the two countries last year 
alar the marketing name for daminozide leaped into the 
international picture in late february when a consumer group the 
natural resources defense council alleged in a report that eating 
apples treated with the growth regulator increased cancer risk in 
children 
alar helps make apples red and keep them crisp 
although the federal government pronounced apples safe to eat 
the resulting consumer uproar hurt domestic and international apple 
sales and caused severe economic damage to apple growers sales 
dropped so sharply the federal government recently agreed to step in 
and purchase 15 million worth of apples to help growers 
washington produces about half the nations apples 
taiwan one of washingtons largest apple markets dropped its 
apple imports dramatically as a result of the alar report 
the cherry scare is an outgrowth of a recent south korean boycott 
of florida grapefruit after a consumer group in south korea 
contended that a government study reported alar in some grapefruit 
but no one seems sure how a link was made to cherries 
a few years ago alar was used on some cherries but there is no 
alar on the 1989 crop and alar has never been used on grapefruit to 
my knowledge said bryant 
industry officials speculate that the alar rumors were started by 
agriculture interests in the two countries who are afraid of foreign 
competition 
domestic farmers in both countries are looking for any way to 
keep foreign agriculture products out of their markets bryant 
said 
washington produced about 55 million boxes of cherries this 
year worth about 100 million there are about three weeks left in 
the current season 
