housing construction reflecting lower interest 
rates rebounded 70 percent in june after falling for four straight 
months and reaching the lowest level in may since 1982 the 
government said today 
fixed mortgage rates which peaked at 1122 percent in march 
before falling to 1007 percent by the end of june had been blamed 
for the recent decline in housing activity 
the commerce department reported that new homes and apartments in 
june were built at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 140 million 
units up from 131 million units in may when construction fell 25 
percent 
junes increase was the highest since an 86 percent hike to 151 
million units in february 1988 it reflected a 280 percent increase 
in apartment construction the highest since a 43 percent increase 
in april 1988 
mays overall drop had been the fourth consecutive one adding up 
to the longest string of declines since activity slowed for five 
months in a row from february through june 1987 the may level was 
the slowest pace since the 130 million rate in december 1982 
the housing industry had been among the sectors of the economy 
hardest hit as interest rates edged upward over the past year with 
the federal reserve seeking to restrain economic growth to contain 
inflation 
analysts said the decline in mortgage rates had come too late to 
help the housing industry in may but thought activity would pick up 
as rates continued to fall 
construction of singlefamily homes fell 20 percent in june to 
an annual rate of 975000 units the lowest level since august 1984 
when 967000 units were recorded they fell 51 percent in may and 
47 percent in april 
but apartment construction rose last month to an annual rate of 
425000 units construction of multifamily units had risen 26 
percent in may after falling 266 percent in april 
by region overall housing construction decreased last month by 
50 percent in the northeast where starts fell to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of 171000 units 
the midwest also recorded a drop down 33 percent to 238000 
units 
the west on the other hand posted a huge 214 percent increase 
to 443000 units starts in the south were up 58 percent to 548000 
units 
applications for building permits a barometer of future housing 
activity were down 35 percent however following a 10 percent 
increase in may and an 85 percent hike in april they had fallen 
the three previous months 
