<TEXT>
refaat elsayed an immigrant who became 
a business tycoon and national hero was convicted of fraud and 
insider trading wednesday and sentenced to five years in prison 
elsayed 43 was convicted on 14 counts of swindling investers 
perjury insider trading and fraud in the biggest whitecollar case 
brought to a swedish court 
the stockholm district court also sentenced gaston portofaix the 
finance manager of elsayeds former company fermenta ab to one 
year in jail portofaix said he would appeal the verdict 
an immigrant who came from egypt in 1964 elsayed parlayed his 
1981 purchase of the failing biotechnical company fermenta into a 
financial empire based on pharmaceuticals 
charm and informality in the normally tightlaced swedish 
business world won him public attention the popular press was 
enamored with his tieless style and his weekend soccerplaying in 
the fifth league as his personal fortune grew to become swedens 
largest 
in 1985 elsayeds wealth in fermenta stock alone was estimated 
at 1 billion kronor or about 156 million 
his business acumen also was admired by a nation emerging from 
recession into prosperity swedish television voted him man of the 
year in 1985 
his success began to unravel the following year when it was 
discovered that his claim to have a doctorate degree was phony the 
disclosure led to a closer look at the companys transactions and 
elsayed was found to have put misleading information in annual 
reports to improve the companys profits 
he also was charged with selling off fermenta shares before the 
release of a negative report 
elsayed declared bankruptcy in 1987 when fermentas shares 
became worthless and he was ousted from the companys management 
the court ruled that elsayed had grossly misused his position 
and the special trust as head of fermenta to mislead the stock 
market 
it said there were no extenuating circumstances and ruled that 
elsayed was forbidden from heading a company in sweden for a 
fiveyear period 
elsayed has been held in jail since may 25 when the court ruled 
he might try to flee the country if freed swedish prison boards 
routinely remit half the sentence 
